
MOTORS CSP SYSTEM v1.2
(c) Defence Research Establishment Valcartier
    Steven Woods, Defence Scientist

This software is currently under development.  This released version may be
thought of as Version 0.5.  It has been distributed by the author with the
understanding that the source is only to be used for research purposes within
Defence Research Establishment Valcartier, and that this copyright notice
should remain with the source code.  Neither the code nor the concepts
embedded within should be shared outside DREV.  

An internal technical paper describing this work is also in development.  A
brief paper describing some of the aspects of this work has been approved for
release outside DREV.  This work is unclassified.

Steven Woods
Aug 4, 1993  Release V0.5


Corrections 
	1. Constraint propagation (AC-3) algorithm in error for MPR as a
	result of incorrect handling of the variable lists.
		Corrected, July 20, 1993 sgw	in v0.5

	2. Believe it or not, #1 was fixed incorrectly.  Repaired and
	double checked - it should work now.
		Corrected, Aug 19, 1993	sgw	in v0.6

	3. Added ability for MPR one line output for compiling test results
	   Made explicit reference to variable ordering and contraint appl
	    ordering in the form of control flags
		Changes verified Aug 25, 1993 sgw  in v0.7

	4. Added Denis McGonigal source code
	   Currently not tied into MOTORS, but available as separate 
	    functions for experimentation
		ac4.lisp  ** currently not functioning, see ac4.problems
		acq.lisp  ** partial arc consistency algs indep tested OK
		Changes verified Aug 25, 1993 sgw  in v0.8

	5. Added Ch11 from TechReport as UserManual.  Note this is already 
	out of data with respect to control for random var inst and 
	constraint order application.
		Aug 28/93 sgw in v1.01

	6. Add Ch1 and Index from TechReport as background and sales pitch for
	other work.
		Aug 28/93 sgw in v1.01

	7. Repairs to work with Allegro Common Lisp completed.	
	   This is now V1.20 but not saved as such.

		Nov 3/94 sgw no new version yet.
	   New Source code in C++ under way.  Observed that lisp code
	   constitutes about 4600 lines of code without comments, 	
	   5300 lines of code with comments.  Old examples on new SPARC
	   server function about with about 4-5 times less CPU seconds,
	   making even complex situations solvable in reasonable time.


